properties.title: silenced
properties.description: Sandy Phimester posted a photo: "Like an Ember from the Fire" A new series of mine... A slight departure from what I normally do, this shoot felt, and still feels really different to me for some reason. I usually shoot a lot of portraits, a bunch of fashion, and some weddings, throw in a little abstract or just walking around town shots, and you have what I normally do. This though, while is a portrait I suppose, is a lot more theatrical or cinematic I suppose. A lot of carefully crafted ambient light, and a lot of props were used, in fact the whole thing is prop driven. The general theme was that of a washed up, used and forgotten actress or theater star, past her prime and no longer important to the community on which she gave so much. It takes place sometime in the past, perhaps the late 1970's or early 1980's. She is in her rehearsal room before the big show, and then out on stage getting ready for the doors to open, her last performance perhaps. Something along those lines. The actual location is New City, well, it WAS New City. A local bar/club that was quite popular for many years, this wasn't it's first location (it used to be further down Jasper Ave in some little hole, that is long gone now)... but it was it's biggest (so far anyway), and most popular. The photoshoot was mere days before the place was closed for good. There was access to a different part, an old theater stage (we used the main stage instead), but it was full of clutter and just looked way too busy and full up of junk. So, not wanting to bother with that, we decided to just create our own look from scratch. I have some early plans for more shoots similar to this soon, more.... cinematic. Drama, perhaps?

properties.title: Edmonton City Hall
properties.description: El Trinidad posted a photo: 1 Sir Winston Churchill Square in downtown Edmonton. An elegant structure in contemporary design, the City Hall of Edmonton is a renovated public building. Rebuilt in the year 1992, the structure is the work of the Dub Architects of Edmonton. The glass pyramid of the main building faces a grand fountain that is used as an ice skating rink in winter. The City Hall not only houses important government offices, but is also the venue for numerous public events. Facilities within the hall can also be hired for private functions. Visitors can take a break at the Kids in the Hall Bistro and make purchases at the souvenir store called Edmonton Shop. [Wikipedia]- Edmonton is the capital of the Canadian province of Alberta and is the province's second-largest city. Edmonton is located on the North Saskatchewan River and is the centre of the Edmonton Capital Region, which is surrounded by the central region of the province. 2011 -Edmonton, Alberta, Canada

properties.title: Art Gallery of Alberta
properties.description: El Trinidad posted a photo: 2 Sir Winston Churchill Square in downtown Edmonton. [Wikipedia]- The Art Gallery of Alberta (AGA) is the city's largest single gallery. Formerly housed in an inconspicuous 1970s building downtown, the AGA collection had over 5,000 pieces of art. The former AGA building was demolished in July 2007 to make way for construction of a new facility designed by Randall Stout. It was estimated to cost over $88-million and the amount that Edmonton City Council donated towards its construction was met with some controversy. The AGA officially opened the weekend of January 30/31, 2010. 2011 -Edmonton, Alberta, Canada

properties.title: Jessica 1 of 100 Strangers
properties.description: jtait_CDN posted a photo: This is the start of my 100 Strangers project. It was a fun start and I am looking forward to the next 99. I was out walking around downtown Edmonton at dusk after a hard rain, and was taking a few pictures of a bench when Jessica walked out of the building. She was part of a wine and chocolate tasting bachelorette party, hence the apron. She is a hairstylist from just outside the city, so of course she was bursting with conversation. When I asked for the picture she told me she doesn't look good in pictures; that's what they all say. I wish I had taken my 50 mm prime with me. Handheld at this time of night, I had to go to ISO 1600 and a 1/15 shutter speed, so the picture is a bit grainy.
